The aim of this retrospective study was to evaluate the clinical performance of 
cobalt-chromium (Co-Cr) single crowns. Ninety restorations were placed in 55 
patients, and follow-up examinations were performed annually for 5 years. Six 
patients (8 crowns) were regarded as dropouts. During the follow-up period, 15 
(17%) crowns/abutment teeth experienced some type of complication; 8 (9%) of 
these were regarded as failures. The cumulative survival rate was estimated at 
90.3% over 5 years, though only 3 (3%) crowns had complications that could be 
related to the crown material. The results suggest that Co-Cr single crowns are 
a promising alternative to other alloys used in fixed prosthodontics.

